SIMPLE: preposterous
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Preposterous
<hw>Pre*pos"ter*ous</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>a.</pos> <ety>[L.
<ets>praeposterus</ets>; <ets>prae</ets> before + <ets>posterus</ets>
coming after, latter. See <er>Posterior</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>Having that first which ought to be last; inverted
in order.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The method I take may be censured as <qex>preposterous</qex>,
because I thus treat last of the antediluvian earth, which was first in
the order of nature.</q> <rj><qau>Woodward.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Contrary to nature or reason; not adapted to the
end; utterly and glaringly foolish; unreasonably absurd;
perverted.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧Most <xex>preposterous</xex> conclusions.⟦rdquo⟧
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q><qex>Preposterous</qex> ass, that never read so far!</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- Absurd; perverted; wrong; irrational; foolish;
monstrous. See <er>Absurd</er>.</syn>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p>-- <wordforms><wf>Pre*pos"ter*ous*ly</wf>, <pos>adv.</pos>
-<wf>Pre*pos"ter*ous*ness</wf>, <pos>n.</pos></wordforms>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Prepostor</ent>⟦br⟧
